MOQ, Turnaround Time, and Lead Times Explained for First-Time Wholesale Buyers
Starting Wholesale? Here’s What No One Tells You
So you’ve decided to dip your toe into wholesale. Maybe you’re launching a small streetwear line. Maybe you're ordering merch for a team fundraiser. Or maybe you’re an event vendor gearing up for the summer rush.
No matter your reason, the first wholesale order can feel more like decoding a foreign language than placing a simple purchase.
Terms like MOQ, turnaround time, and lead time get thrown around like everyone already knows what they mean. But if you’re new to the game, they can cause confusion—and worse, costly delays.
This blog is your cheat sheet. We’re breaking it all down: what each term means, how they affect your timeline, and how to plan like a pro.
MOQ: What It Really Means (And Why It’s Non-Negotiable)
MOQ stands for Minimum Order Quantity—the lowest number of units a supplier will agree to produce in a single run. If you’re thinking small batch, this number matters more than you think.
It’s not just a random threshold. It’s tied to how production works. Manufacturers operate on efficiency. The higher the quantity, the lower the cost per unit. The lower the quantity? The harder it is to justify the setup time, labor, and materials.
Let’s say you’re ordering custom mesh shorts. If the MOQ is 100 units, you can’t order 60 and hope they’ll “make an exception.” They probably won’t. Or if they do, it’ll cost you more per piece—sometimes a lot more.
Instead of seeing MOQ as a barrier, think of it as a lever. It forces you to think strategically: Who will these sell to? How fast will they move? Can I presell them before I order?
Pro tip: Smart sellers don’t fight the MOQ. They build their drop around it.
Turnaround Time: The Clock Starts After You Pay
Turnaround time is often misunderstood. Many first-time buyers assume the countdown begins the moment they request a quote. It doesn’t.
Turnaround time is the number of business days it takes to produce your order after final approval and payment. That means if you’re still tweaking your design or haven’t signed off on the proof, the clock hasn’t even started ticking.
Let’s say the turnaround is 10 business days. That doesn’t include weekends. It also doesn’t include shipping. If you approve your mockup on a Friday and pay Monday, production starts Tuesday. Ten business days later, your order ships—not arrives.
If you’re working against a deadline, build in buffer time. Always.
Need gear for a tournament on the 15th? Don’t place your order on the 1st. Place it two weeks earlier. That gives you time for mockups, approvals, and any hiccups that may pop up.
Lead Time: The Bigger Picture You Can’t Ignore
While turnaround time refers specifically to production, lead time is the total time between placing your order and receiving your product. It includes everything—design revisions, production, shipping, and even potential backlogs.
Think of lead time as your full runway. It’s the difference between a smooth launch and a panic-laced email chain asking, “Where’s my order?”
Here’s how it breaks down:
•	Lead time = proofing + turnaround + shipping
•	If proofing takes 3 days, turnaround takes 10 business days, and shipping takes 5 days, your total lead time is three weeks or more.
That’s assuming everything goes perfectly. But what if your design needs revisions? Or your payment gets delayed? Or the product you want is backordered?
Lead time planning is about more than logistics. It’s about peace of mind. It’s the difference between scrambling and scaling.
The Real-World Impact of Not Planning Ahead
Let’s talk about Marcus.
Marcus runs a small fan shop for a semi-pro basketball league. He wanted shorts with each team’s logo for a three-day playoff event in June. He reached out to a supplier at the end of May. He figured two weeks was more than enough time.
It wasn’t.
The supplier’s MOQ was 120 units per design. Marcus needed five versions—one for each team. He hadn’t finalized artwork. He didn’t have team rosters confirmed. And he didn’t factor in shipping time from the West Coast.
By the time he got the last logo approved, turnaround had only just started. The shorts arrived the day after the tournament ended.
Marcus didn’t just lose sales. He lost trust with his buyers.
Lesson? Late merch is unsellable merch.
How To Avoid First-Time Buyer Pitfalls
Wholesale isn’t complicated, but it is time-sensitive. The most common mistakes new buyers make aren’t about product quality—they’re about timing.
Here’s how to avoid them:
•	Start earlier than you think. If you think you need four weeks, give yourself six.
•	Ask about current turnaround times. They fluctuate during busy seasons.
•	Don’t assume express shipping saves the day. Factories don’t “rush” production unless you pay for it—and even then, capacity matters.
•	Use pre-orders to validate volume. Hit your MOQ before spending a dime.
•	Get everything in writing. Quotes, timelines, proofs—document it all.
Planning isn’t just about logistics. It’s about protecting your momentum.
MOQ and Lead Time by Product Type
Not all products are created equal. A small run of custom-printed tees might take a week. But embroidered items, multi-color screen prints, or cut-and-sew garments? Those need more runway.
Understanding how each product type impacts your timeline helps you plan smarter and avoid last-minute surprises.
Here’s a general breakdown of common wholesale apparel categories, keeping in mind that exact numbers will vary by supplier:
Custom Mesh Shorts
•	Typical MOQ: 50–100 pieces
•	Turnaround Time: 10–15 business days
•	Notes: Add extra time for embroidery, woven labels, or finishing touches
Screen-Printed Tees
•	Typical MOQ: 24–48 pieces
•	Turnaround Time: 7–10 business days
•	Notes: Simpler, single-color designs speed things up
Embroidered Caps
•	Typical MOQ: 48–72 pieces
•	Turnaround Time: 12–18 business days
•	Notes: Digitizing your logo adds setup time
Cut & Sew (Fully Custom Garments)
•	Typical MOQ: 100+ pieces
•	Turnaround Time: 3–6 weeks
•	Notes: Premium results, but longer timelines due to patterning and construction
Not every vendor will offer all these items. And not every option fits every budget or use case. But knowing how MOQ and production time vary by product gives you better control over your drop schedule—and your bottom line.
What Experienced Buyers Do Differently
There’s a reason experienced merch sellers rarely scramble. They’ve learned how to work the system instead of getting worked by it.
Here’s what they do that first-timers often don’t:
1.	They build a calendar backward. Start from your launch date and work back to figure out when to order.
2.	They batch orders. Instead of five small orders, they run one big drop to hit MOQs and save per unit.
3.	They use templates. Reusing approved designs and sizes speeds up reorders.
4.	They communicate early and often. The best vendors are partners, not vending machines. Keep them in the loop.
5.	They prepare for Plan B. Alternate colorways. Backup shipping methods. Contingency is power.
The more you plan, the more you profit. Simple as that.
Final Thoughts: MOQ, Turnaround, and Lead Time Aren’t Barriers—They’re Tools
If you’re stepping into wholesale for the first time, it’s easy to feel boxed in by acronyms and timelines. But these concepts aren’t here to slow you down. They exist to help you scale with clarity.
MOQ helps keep production efficient. Turnaround time sets realistic expectations. Lead time lets you plan for real-world delays.
When you understand them—and use them to your advantage—you shift from reactive to proactive. From guessing to growing. From “I hope this works” to “I know this will sell.”
